message.content:
To align a row of divs to the right using Flexbox in CSS, you'll want to set the container element's display property to "flex", and then use the justify-content property with the value "flex-end". Here is an example:

HTML:
```html
<div class="container">
  <div>Div 1</div>
  <div>Div 2</div>
  <div>Div 3</div>
</div>
```
CSS:
```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: flex-end;
}

/* This will give equal width to each div */
.container > div {
  flex: 1;
  border: 1px solid black;
  padding: 10px;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}
```
In this example, the container element has a class of "container" and contains three child divs. The CSS styles for ".container" set the display property to "flex", which enables Flexbox for that element. Then, the justify-content property is set to "flex-end", which aligns the divs along the right side of the container. The flex property in ".container > div" gives equal width to each div.
